{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/00340580928/1945082401/0290.xml":{"full_text":"f What's. happened to Hitler?\u2019 Is he\n~dealt or alive? If dead, does his ghost\nstill walk?\nThere are signs of his continuing\nr handiwork in these United States, as\nwell as ip such obvious haunts as Fas\ncist Spain and Argentina.\nJew-baiting and Negro -baiting\nspeeches are made in Washington by\ncharacters like. Bilbo and Rankin.\nAtnerican \u201cnationalists\" run rampant,\nnot furtively but seeking publicity, to\nget'more money from the frightened\nrich. Whole newspaper chains fea\ntore Hitleristic \u201cred scares\u201d apd prop\naganda for another world war.\n-And now President O. A- Knight of\nthe Oil Workers International Union\nand Secretary W. M. Akin of the\n-\u2022Texas CIO Council, have uncovered a\nHitleristic plot in our own Southwest.\n;-'vYjj4\n\u25a0iif.-v.\nThe CIO leaders have submitted to\nTexas Attorney General' Grover Sell\ners -a. secret unsigned memorandum\nsent to businessmen in the Rio\nGrande Valley. They, charge it is\nsponsored by William Walker, chair\nman of an outfit known as \u201cFight for\nFree Enterprise.\u201d\nThe memorandum 'contains a pro\ngram for fighting union organization\natnoPg agricultural and cannery work\ners in the Valley, and asks for funds\nfor tin anti-CIO crusade.\nIt outlines plans for an anonymous\nsefttp, referred to as \u201cThe Organiza\ntion,\u201d which is to be \u201cthe \u2018Front\u2019 for\nattacking,the CIO vigorously and re\nlentlessly on behalf of those who. for\nobvious reasons, cannot now make\n{themselves the target for reprisals.\u201d\n\n\u25a0yt;\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n1\n\n\n\n\nIh\nlaas\n1-\n\np%\nI\n\n\nV;.'\nKi\n,v:\ni'C. i\nThe propose^ methods of attack\nneatly combine the doctrines of Kfein\nKampf and the common practices of\n.American- union-busters. They in\nclude:.\n(1) A press campaign designed 10\nidentify the CIO with \u201cCommunism\u201d\nand \u201catheism.\u201d\n(2) A scheme for a' Writ of Man\ndamus against the Texas Attorney\nQeheral, under, which qn opportunity\nmight he afforded for. \u201callegations of\na, sensational nature without regard to\nlibel,\u201d which\u2018Slahders the newspapers\nmight print \u201cwith complete immunity\nfr6m. any action by CIO.\u201d I\nIfaifid pro^rauts., \"flaying, the..\nCl,(j.\u201d But- such attacks are to be \u201cin\nterspersed among other current topics\nto refute any charge that this is splely\nart anti-CIO program\u201d\u2014and* \u201cin order\nto split labor,\u201d praise is proposed for\n\u201ctlie general -purpose of old-line\nAmerican unionism.\u201d\n(4) Creation of \u201cperiodical sensa\ntion\u201d by publication of purported CIO\ndocuments to \"inflame public opinion\nand arouse resentment and opposi\ntion.\u201d While stopping short of de\nscribing such documents as forgeries,\nthe memorandum cynically comments\nthat \u201cno amount of CIO denial will\ndestroy the effect of such releases.\"\n(5) \u201cDischarged veterans will\nbe carefully selected ior toughness\nand peculiar abilities and set to work\norganizing \u2018Americanism Protective\nCommittees\u2019 to oppose 700 activi\nties, and to become political campaign\norganizations in the spring of 1946.\"\nFascist violence is also suggested by\npaying that these \u201cwill also become\ndirect action committees\u201d for \u201ccoun\nteracting any strong-arm work at\ntempted by the CIO.\u201d\n(6) \u201cPunitive action\u201d' against\nnewspapers fair to CJO, including\n\u2018pressure on advertisers to withdraw\ntheir patronage.*\n(7) Frame-ups against CIO mem\nbers. Billboards with \u201cvitriolicv at\ntacks on the CIO\u201d are proposed, in\n\u25a0\u2018.which connection \u201ccertain peace offi\ncers will enter into an understanding\nwith\u2019 \u2018The Organization\u2019 whereby the\nCIO hoodlums will be trapped in at\ntempts to destroy these billboards^\u2019\n\u201cAn intensive campaign in the\n,1946 primaries to nominate Democra\ntic candidates bitterly opposed to the\nCIO.\u201d f*\nBefore. yon dismiss this plot as\n\u201ccjackpot\u201d stuff, consider its ingredi\nents\u2014and recall that Hitler himself\nwas' once scoffed at as a \u201charmless\ncrackpot.\u201d\nHere is Hitler\u2019s \u201cBolshevik men\nace;\u201d his \u2018\u2018big lie\u201d technique; his fund\nraising from anti-labor employers;\nhis Reichstag fir* frameup and forg\neries; his divide-and-conquer; his\nStorm-Troop hoodlumism; his su\nborning of press and police; and his\ncombination of political demagogy\nwith mob violence.\nT^hen remember that all of these de\nvices have had their American preced\nents and parallels in past union-bust\ning campaigns.\nONE\nFOR ALL\nOFFICIAL PUBLICATION OF ORGANIZED LABOR IN AKRON AND VICINITY\nALL FOR\nONE\nCooperate! With A. t. of L. and CIO Labor Union* of Summit, Medina,- Portage, Wayne and Surrounding Counties Member of Intemationai Labor Pres* gf America,\nVol 23 No. 33\nAKRON, OHIO, FRIDAY, AUGUST 24, 1945\n$2.00 PER YEAR\nAKRON INDUSTRIAL UNION COUNCIL\nC*''\nif.\nm\nTO DISCUSS RECONVERSION PLANS\n\u25a0:\u00a3tt\n10 Point Reconversion\nProgram Ottered by\nAFL Executives\nChicago\u2014Labor rallied the nation for an all-out effort to win\nthe peace the moment the fighting ended.\nIn the midst of rejoicing over the official announcem'ent of\nVJ-Day, the. Executive Council issued a solemn warning that peace\nfnay bring misery to the American people within the next few\nmonths. ~i\nPointing the way for action to speed\nrapid postwar recovery, the AFL lead\ners offered the following program:\n1. Speed up reconversion to the limit.\n2. Give highest priority to expansion\nof peacetime production\n3. Increase wage rates to provide vit\nally necessary purchasing power and to\nprevent impairment of living standards.\n,4. Raise unemployment compensation\nin line with President Truman\u2019s emer\ngency recommendations to,Congress.\n5. Lift minimum wage floor to 65\ncents an hour immediately and 75 cents\nwithin 3 years.\n6. Restore free collective bargaining\nimmediately, as the .National War La*\nbor feoard\"prepares to go out of exis\ntence.\n7. End wartime government controls\njver labor and industry promptly.\n(Continued on Page Four;\nFascist Plots\nUncovered by\nTexas CIO\nA conspiracy on the part of Fight\nfor Free Enterprise to use the courts\nof Texas to persecute ,the CIO was\ncharged this week by President O. A.\nKnight of the CIO Oil Workers\nUnion and Secretary W. M. Akin of\nthe Texas- CIO Council, on the basis\nof documents submitted to Attorney\nGeneral Grover Sellers and the U. S.\nDepartment of Justice.\nNewspapers Were to be coerced,\nframed up ^videnc.e was to be manu\nfactured, and unsubstantiated charges\nwere to be levelled against the CIO in\nsuch a way that the libel laws could,\nhe evaded, it was charged\nCl6 representatives named William\nWalker, chairman of Fight for Free\nEnterprise, with headquarters in San\nAntonio, as the sponsor of a secret\nmemorandum sent to business men in\nthe Rio Grande valley. The memor\nandum contained Walker\u2019s program\nfor fighting union organization among\nagricultural and cannery workers in\nthe 'Valley, and asked for funds for an\nanti-CIO crusade.\nThe 'memorandum was marked\n\"confidential\u201d and was unsigned. It\n(Continued on Page Four)\nFRAN KEN STEEN VICTORY\nIS HAILED BY CIO PAC\nThe sweeping victory of UAW vice\npresident Richard T. Frankensteen\nand and other PAC-supported, candi\ndates in the Detroit primary contests\nrecently was hailed by Sidney Hill\nman, chairman of the CIO Political\nAction Committee, as another tri\numph for labor and progressive forces\nin municipal campaign throughout the\nnation, t j\nIn a surprisingly heavy Vote, proof\nof PAC\u2019s ability to get voters to the\npolls Frankensteen ran. first in the\nrace for mayoralty nomination well\nahead of the incumbent, Edward J.\nJeffries. Under the non-partisan rule,\nthey will be the opposing candidates\nin the November run-off. The popu\nlar UAW official, first top labor of\nficial to run for an important office\nsince PAC was organized, rolled up\nCOURT CASE\nAIDS LABOR\nWhen the Court of Appeals rend\nered a decision this month to the ef\nfect that Harvey Edward Chambers\nwas entitled to continue to receive un\nemployment compensation benefits\nafter he had refused to accept a non\nunion job, the trade union movement\nscored one of the most far-reaching\nvictories \u2018attained in recent years, ac\ncording to Phil Hannah. Secretary\nTreasu'rer of the Ohio State Federa\ntion of Labor.\nMr. Chambers, Columbus carpenter,\na member of Local No. 200 (AFL)\nbecame unemployed on Dec. 9, 1942.\nHe applied for and was allowed bene\nfits by the Bureau of Unemployment\nCompensation, but eventually the\nbenefits were ordered stopped by the\u2019\nBoard of Review because he r'efused\nto accept an offer of work to which\nhe was referred by the Bureau.\nThe job to which Mr. Chambers\nwas referred was non-union .and he\nrefused to accept it because of that\nfact and because, under the rules of\nthe union, if he had begun the em\n(Continued on Page 2)\nAIUC Notice\nThe next regular business meet\ning fit Akron Industrial Union\nCouncil will be held Friday night,\nAugust 24th, in the auditorium of\nGoodrich Local No. 5, United Rub\nI ber Workers of America, 708 South\nMain street. The meeting will be\ncalled to order ht 7:30 o'clock by\nPresident F. B. Van Houten. This\nannouncement constitutes the of\nficial notice of the meeting to all\ndelegates and other persons desir\ning to be present.\nThe next regular meeting of the\nOrganization Committee of the\nCouncil will be held on Wednesday1\nnight, September 12th the Coun\ncil's offices at 714 South Main\nstreet. The Executive Committee\nwill hold its next regular meeting\nin the Council\u2019s offices on .Thurs\nday night, September 13th.\nI _._\nI .1.\n82,836 votes against Jeffries\u2019 68,7a4.\nCounty Auditor James* D. priel ran\nthird with 35,720 and it was believed1\nin Detroit political circles that his\nsuppo'rt would go to- Frankensteen.\nHillman emphasize^' that Franken\nsteen was tfae latest <|f PAC-support\ned candidates to emCTge a.Victor in\nlocal primary and run-off Contests.\nThe PAC chairman \"pointed 'to the.\nsuccesses achieved in Minneapolis,\nBirmingham, Los Angeles and New\nark. N. J., where PAC-backfed candi\ndates were victorious.\n\u201cOnly qne conclusion can be drawn\nfrom Mr. Frankensteen\u2019s well de\nserved victory. The people of Detroit\nare determined to have a local admin\nistration concerned \"with the grave\nproblems of reconversion, full produc\n(Continued on Page 2)\nJUST COMMON SENSE\nAn Editorial 1\nNow that reconversion has been thrust on ns with a bang, the\ntime to use real ^common sense is more essential than ever. Our\nentire future easily can depend on cool, clear thinking.\nIn order to* maintain the present standard of living, Labor is\nasking that hours be shortened and pay increased. Nothing is more\nsound than this. Purchasing power must be maintained at its present\nlevel in order that a ready market be created fqr the great amount of\npeacetime products to be manufactured.\nThe reason for this is simple. It has been proven time and time\nagain. If the millions of workers in the nation do not have sufficient\nmoney with which to purchase manufactured articles, the whe.els of\nindustry soon must slow down. This, in turn, throws additional men\nartel women out of employment, thus further reducing the purchas\ning power of the nation. Such conditions are the cause of depres\nsions\u2014vicious depressions that mean misery and want for millions.\nTljis must not happen again.\nShorter working hours and increased pay also mean more men\nand women employed. This means additional purchasing power, and\njust as fewer jobs spell depression, more jobs mean the manufactur\ner of additional products, additional employes and higher living\nstandards for the masses.\nA few hard-headed industrialists who refuse to grant their em\nployes shorter hours and higher pay easily can wreck our entire\neconomic structure. Postwar industry naturally will be highly com\npetitive. If a few industrialists refuse to raise wages and shorten\nworking hours, the rest must do the same in order tb compete in the\nipen markets, regardless of what the ultimate economic loss may\nbe.\n\nThen, too, there is the national debt to consider. It was con\ntracted during the wartime boom. Any radical deflation at this time\n;V*a deflation thatjeasily can be caused by_ industrialists refusing to\n^eed Labor\u2019s request forTiigher wagesTand shorter working hours\u2014\nin reality will mean an increase in the size of that debt. We don\u2019t\nmean the1 debt will be increased in actual dollars, but it is equivalent\nto that, for as the purchasing power of the dollar declines, it will\ntake jjist that many more dollar-values to pay off the debt. It really\nis something to think about. v\nWe met and conquefed every wartime problem that confronted\nus. The peacetime problems are no greater. They just heed the\napplication of the same amount of good comrrion sense that we used\n/during the waf. Let us not make the mistake of being a penny wise\nand a pound foolish. That is false economy. The price really is too\ngreat. Let\u2019s all use good common sense.\nSPEAK UP!\nBy RUTH TAYLOR\nCenturies ago Euripedes wrote, \u201cA slave is he who cannot ex\npress his thoughts.\u201d\nHow can you expect people to understand you if you cannot\nspeak for yourself? How can you expect the proper evaluation of\nyour work and your ability unless you are able to t^lk of it clearly,\nquietly and with dignity?\nNow don\u2019t say \u2018\u2018I can\u2019t talk about myself.\u201d Well if you can\u2019t,\nwho can?\nI don\u2019t mean you\u2019re to go around loud-mouthed, bragging about\nwhat you mean to do someday. You must have, or acquire if you,\nhaven\u2019t it, the ability to sell yourself\u2014but remember you have to'\nhave something to sell before you begin. You\u2019ve got to be sure your\nChicago, and many other big cities would probably be in shambles\nto have (the assurance of ability and competence before you start\ntalking and not just be a bag of \"hot air\nAnd it wasn\u2019t just yourself Euripedes meant. \u201cA slave is he\nwho cannot express his thoughts.\u201d You have lots of ideas about the\nthings that, interest you. (I\u2019ve met very few people whose only in\nterest was themselves.) Learn how to talk about the things that in\nterest you. Practice by saying what you think. It 11 come hard at\nfirst\u2014like anything new,. But the more you do it, the easier it will\nbecome. I know*\u2014it wasn\u2019t easy for me at first, either.\n4 Have something to say\u2014evtn if it is only thank you. I know\none trade unionist who was suddenly catapulted to an important job.\nHe was a big frog in his own puddle but when he attended his first\nbig convention very few people had ever heard of him. They knew\nhim before the end of it! I never heard a man make so many tvfo\nminute speeches. When you summed thent*all up, all he did was\nthank the previous speaker for his \"apt and appropriate remarks.\nOf course, all the speakers he complimented\u2014and their followers\u2014\ndecided he was aonan of discernment. And, when he finally had\nsomething to say\u2014they listened they were his friends.-Now,\ncouldn\u2019t you do that?\nRemember the oftener you take the trouble to put your\nthoughts into words, the clearer you will think and the better able\nyou will be to explain your viewpoint. You will gain confidence and\npoise. You will feel more capable and better able to tackle not only\nvour job, but the one ahead.'\n\"A slave is he who cannot express his thoughts.\u201d\n\"v.- vi*\u2022\nSalvage of Goodyear f\nAircraft Plants Is i f\nPart of Program i|\nPlans for a definite reconversion program in Akron\u2014a program\nthat will provide more employment at higher wages\u2014will ibe dis\ncussed. Friday night at the meeting of Akron Industrial Union Coun\ncil in Goodrich Local\u2019s hall, 708 South Main Street. t\nLABOR AIDS\nIN RELIEF\nHungry and unfortunate people\nthroughout the world will share in\n$2,750,000 worth of necessities tagged\n\u201cFrom American Labor.\u201d\nThe $2,750,000 comes from an alloca\ntion by the National War Fund. Labor\nwill administer the .expenditure of this\nparticular sum in the millions to be\nspent for relief abroad by the War\nFund following its fall campaign for\nfunds.\nTotal of Labor\u2019s 1946 allocations\nwill be less than in 1945. This is be\ncause Britain has dissolved its war le\nlief organization in America and Rus\nsia h\u00bbs left) the National War Fund.\nLabor\u2019s program calls.for cash relief\nto families of Gestapo victims in Bel\ngium, Czechoslovakia, France, and Lux\nembourg vocational education in\nChina, Czechoslovakia; rest homes,\nclinics for returning prisoners of war,\nslave laborers in Belgium and\" Czecho\nslovakia.\nChina will receive the\u2019 largest share\nof Labor\u2019s funds. Much of the money\nwill be used to bolster morale in that\ncountry's war with Japan.\nDuring the past two years, th\u00a3 Chi\nnese Association of Labor established\n(Continued on Page 4)\nWeekly Labor\nRadio Shows\nUnited Rubber Workers of\nAmerica will broadcast a program\neach Wednesday evening' at 6:30\nover Radio Station WHKK, Ak\nron, 640 on your dials, for tbe en\ntertainment and education of all\nlisteners in the greater Akron area.\nThe program will be transcribed\nand repeated each Wednesday\nnight at 10:30 o'clock. It is a\nworth-while program. Listen to it\neach Wednesday. _\nThe' \u201cAFL Radio Show\u201d is a\nregular Saturday night feature of\nRadio Station WAKR. It comes\non the air at 6:45 and lasts until\n7 o\u2019clock. It is a very good pro\ngram. Listen to it regularly.\nCharging that the Pennsylvania Rail\nroad has disconnected air-conditioning\nunits on troop trains throughout the\nline\u2019s system, National Director A. B.\nMartin of the United Railroad Workers\nof America, C.I.O.,'today produced a\ncopy of an official PRR train operating\norder which he asserts proves the rail\nroad is transporting troops and veter\nans on a'cattle-car basis.\nThis amazing railroad order to var\nious operating officials along the lines\nof PRR is one of the most astounding\norders since the war began, placing\nAmerican servicemen in a separate cat\negory from civilians who can afford to\npay fancy prices for air-conditioning in\ntheir coaches. This oCder which comes\nto light a year after issuance is still\nin line with PRR policy toward the\nOrp phase of the proposed program\nis to reconvert the plants of Goodyear\nAircraft Corporation to the manufac\nture of peacetime products that will\nguarantee employment for most of\nthe aircraft employes.\nPlans 'to return to the 36-hour\nwork-week with basic pay increases\nof approximately 30 per cent already\nhave been advocated by members of\nGoodrich and Goodyear Local*.\nUnited Rubber Workers of America.\nA similar resolution may be present\ned to Council members at their sched\nuled business meeting.\nThe attempt to salvage Goodyear\nAircraft where someflS.000 employes\nalready have lost theij jot?*;, -will re;\nquire an act of Congress, fn the opin\nion of George R. Bass, executive sec\nretary of the Council. The .plants\nwere erected with government money.\n(Continued on Page Font)\u00abV\nSmack Rumors\nOf Disunity\nIn URWA\nA whispering campaign in Akron\nto the effect that the. Mechanical Ed\nucation Society of 'America is con\nducting a drive here to break up\n\u2022United Rubber Workers of America\nreceived a setback in a resolution ap\nproved Sunday by members of Good\nrich Local No. 5.\nThe resolution declared that unity\nexists within the ranks of the URWA\nand that there is no room for dual v;\nunionism in Akron or in '.he entire. v\nURWA field.\nThe Mechanical Educational So\nciety of America is a so-called inde\npendent Labor movemAt that was\nstarted some time ago in Detroit by\nMatt Smith, a former member of\nUnited Automobile Workers of Amer-\nica. The following resolution, ap\nproved by members of Goodrich Lo\ncal, put the lie to the rumors that the\nnew organization has made headway\nin a rumored attempt to take certain\nlocals out of the URWA:\nWHfeREAS: There have been per\nsistent rumors and cha-ges that cer\ntain groups in the URWA are trying\nto split opr International Union and\n(Continued on Page 2)\ntroops, according to Mr. Martin, He\nalleges thaf there have been instance?\nof hospital coaches on the Pennsyl\nvania Railroad which were not air-con\nditioned.\nThe order stipulates that where win- V S\ndows can be opened, air-conditioned y\nunits are to be entirely disconnected.\nThus, according to Martin,* soldiers\ntraveling across the continent mutt\nbreathe in the dust and soot of a trans\ncontinental trip for 3000 miles. Martin\nis calling to the attention of. the ODT\nand Interstate Commerce Commissiott V\nthe salient factors in this order.\nThe order states:\n\u201cTroop trains are not to be air con\nditioned except where the windows\ncannot be opened. If ice-activated cars\n(Continued on Page Four)\nMM\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nBACK UP THE BOYS\nIM\nWITH BONDS\n\nx i","height":"27416","width":"21580"}}
